Here is the cleaned up text:

Salesforce automatically creates and saves a transcript for each messaging session. Messages exchanged with a bot are also stored in the conversation transcripts.

To be transparent with your customers, you can include this information in the auto-response shown when customers send a message to your company.

Customers might ask your company to handle their data in the following ways:

* Delete personal data associated with a customer who has messaged your company via Messaging.
* Track customers’ approval for how your company interacts with them via Messaging.
* Restrict how Messaging processes personal data.
* Export customer-related data.

You can address these requests by:

* Adding new fields to objects associated with data privacy.
* Deleting the customer’s messaging user records, which deletes all related messaging sessions and transcripts.
* Exporting Messaging conversation transcripts.
* Hiding or replacing sensitive data in messaging sessions and transcripts.
* Encrypting certain fields at rest.

Encryption at rest is supported for certain fields in enhanced Messaging channels and Messaging for In-App and Web. However, encryption at rest isn't supported in standard Messaging channels with Salesforce Classic.

Some Messaging channels aren't able to be certified for HIPAA compliance because their associated third-party applications or technology aren't HIPAA-certified.

To protect customer data, you can also:

* Store customers’ data privacy preferences.
* Customize auto-responses in Service Cloud Messaging Channels.
* Encrypt new data in standard fields.
title: Protecting Customer Data and Privacy in Service Cloud Messaging
